article.description: Tamika Catchings scored eight of her 30 points in overtime, including the tying free throw with 14 seconds left and the winning jumper with 0.1 seconds to go in the Fever's 80-78 victory over the Liberty.
article.headline: Catchings' 30 points spark Fever to OT win vs. Liberty
article.linkText: Catchings' 30 points spark Fever to OT win vs. Liberty
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Tamika Catchings didn't want to give the New York Liberty another shot at the end of overtime.

Catchings scored eight of her 30 points in the extra period, including the tying free throw with 14 seconds left and the winning jumper with 0.1 seconds to go in the Indiana Fever's 80-78 victory over the Liberty on Tuesday night.

"I wanted to make sure we got the last shot," Catchings said. "I heard everyone yelling to run the clock down and then I heard, 'Go! Go! Go!'"

After Becky Hammon hit a jumper with 15.4 seconds left in overtime to give New York a 78-77 lead, Catchings was fouled by Ashley Battle before the Fever (7-3) inbounded the ball. Catchings made the free throw to tie it and Indiana retained possession.

Catchings, selected to the WNBA's All-Decade Team earlier in the night, then hit a 15-footer with time running down.

"It shouldn't come down to the last shot," New York's Kelly Schumacher said. "We made other mental mistakes. If we only executed, it could have been a different outcome. It was a really tough loss."

The Liberty led by five twice in the extra period, the last time at 75-70 after Shameka Christon's 3-pointer with 1:54 left.

Catchings made one free throw, Tully Bevilaqua had a fast-break layup and Catchings made two more from the line to give Indiana a 77-76 lead with 30 seconds left.

The Liberty (2-7) scored five straight points in the final 1:16 of regulation to send the game to the extra period. Hammon, who finished with 17 points, hit a 3-pointer, and Loree Moore tied it at 65 with two free throws with 28.2 seconds left.

Bevilaqua missed a 3-point shot with 12.9 seconds left and Moore corralled the loose ball on the ground and called timeout.

On the Liberty's ensuing possession, Catchings stole the ball from New York's Cathrine Kraayeveld and headed down the court, but Hammon knocked the ball away and off Catchings near the 3-point arc and it went out of bounds.

"Today was one of the toughest losses this year," Hammon said. "We hit a couple of 3s to send it to overtime. We had a couple of big plays down the stretch, but we just couldn't capitalize."

Bevilaqua scored 13 points and Tamika Whitmore and Charlotte Smith added 10 points apiece to help Indiana snap a three-game road losing streak and beat New York for the second time this season. Catchings also had nine rebounds.

"The whole second half was back and forth," Catchings said. "We were not executing properly and showing energy. When they go on their run, we have to answer."

Schumacher, acquired from Indiana in the offseason, scored 16 points for New York, and Barbara Farris added 11.

"We just came up a little short," Liberty coach Pat Coyle said. "We didn't collapse. We went down but we fought back, tied it and had a chance to win it in regulation."

Whitmore, who played for New York from 1999-03, made two free throws to give Indiana a 61-53 lead with 6:28 to go in the fourth quarter.

The Liberty scored five straight points and pulled within three on Farris' layup with 5:16 left.

"We had to be better defensively," Fever coach Brian Winters said. "You have to defend and rebound, and that keeps you in games, especially when your offense struggles."

Indiana had an 11-0 run, capped by Catchings' three-point play, to take a 54-46 lead with 48 seconds left in the third.
